{"key":"post-12428004","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12428004</id>\n<content>I'd disregard the difference between .8 and 1.2 inches of water column.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If you've found a blower that will deliver 400 cfm @ .8&quot; it will work for an 18&quot; X 24&quot; filter.&amp;nbsp; What you want is around 100 lineal feet per minute leaving the face of the flowhood.&amp;nbsp; This means for a 1 square foot filter(12 X 12), you'd want a 100 cfm blower at .8&quot; to 1.2&quot; of static pressure in a perfect world.&amp;nbsp; However, inside the plenum behind a flowhood is not a perfect world, so add about 20% to your calculations to account for friction, turns, blower efficiency, etc.</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12430734</next>\n<prev>12427860</prev>\n<first>12421555</first>\n<last>16428088</last>\n<when>1271809545</when>\n<utime>04/21/10 03:25 AM</utime>\n</post>"}